window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["cardiogenic-shock"]={"slug": "cardiogenic-shock", "title": "Cardiogenic Shock: SCAI Staging, Hemodynamics, and Escalation", "tagline": "A fellowship-depth, bedside-practical approach to recognizing, phenotyping, and escalating cardiogenic shock, from SCAI stage and CPO/PAPi hemodynamics through inotropes, vasopressors, and mechanical circulatory support.", "level": 3, "readMin": 32, "takeaways": ["Cardiogenic shock is a low-output state producing end-organ hypoperfusion despite adequate or elevated intracardiac filling pressures; lactate and the SCAI stage, not blood pressure alone, define severity and track the trajectory.", "The SCAI SHOCK classification (A At risk, B Beginning, C Classic, D Deteriorating, E Extremis), modified by cardiac arrest and by a three-axis (exam, biomarker, hemodynamic) risk gradient, stratifies in-hospital mortality and standardizes communication.", "Cardiac power output (MAP times CO / 451) below roughly 0.6 W and pulmonary artery pulsatility index below about 1.0 are the two hemodynamic numbers that most sharply predict mortality and unmask right ventricular failure at the bedside.", "Norepinephrine is the first-line vasopressor in cardiogenic shock; the DOREMI trial found milrinone and dobutamine clinically equivalent, so inotrope choice is mechanistic, not evidence-mandated.", "Routine IABP does not reduce mortality in AMI shock (IABP-SHOCK II) and routine early VA-ECMO did not improve survival (ECLS-SHOCK), whereas a microaxial flow pump reduced mortality in selected STEMI shock (DanGer Shock) at the cost of more complications, so device selection is patient-specific, not reflexive."], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Define cardiogenic shock hemodynamically and distinguish it from hypovolemic, distributive, and obstructive shock at the bedside and on the PA catheter.", "Apply the SCAI SHOCK stages (A-E) with the cardiac-arrest and three-axis risk-gradient modifiers, and translate a stage into prognosis and urgency.", "Phenotype shock by ventricle (left, right, biventricular) and by wet/cold hemodynamic profile to direct therapy.", "Select and titrate vasopressors and inotropes on a mechanistic and receptor basis, citing DOREMI for inotrope equipoise.", "Interpret cardiac power output and PAPi and use them, with lactate trend, to decide when to escalate to temporary mechanical circulatory support.", "State the evidence and appropriate role of IABP, microaxial flow pumps, and VA-ECMO from IABP-SHOCK II, DanGer Shock, and ECLS-SHOCK."]}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why It Matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Cardiogenic shock remains the leading cause of death after acute myocardial infarction, and short-term mortality has stayed stubbornly near 30 to 50 percent despite decades of device innovation. The reason is rarely a lack of hardware. It is failure of the two disciplines that actually move outcomes: early recognition before end-organ injury is fixed, and disciplined, phenotype-driven escalation rather than reflexive drug or device stacking."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The single most consequential concept in modern shock care is that <strong>time and trajectory beat any one device</strong>. A patient in SCAI stage B who is caught, phenotyped, and supported before lactate climbs and the SCAI stage deteriorates has a fundamentally different prognosis than the same physiology recognized in stage E. Escalate on the slope of the lactate and the CPO, not on a single snapshot.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the four shock buckets: <strong>CHOD</strong> (Cardiogenic, Hypovolemic, Obstructive, Distributive). Cardiogenic and hypovolemic are cold with low CO; distributive is warm with high CO and low SVR; obstructive (tamponade, massive PE, tension pneumothorax) is cold but has a mechanical, often reversible cause you must not miss.", "depth": 1}]}, {"id": "definition-and-physiology", "title": "Definition and Essential Physiology", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Cardiogenic shock is a state of inadequate tissue perfusion caused by primary cardiac dysfunction, in the presence of adequate or elevated intracardiac filling pressures. The defining lesion is a fall in cardiac output that neurohormonal compensation can no longer offset, producing a self-reinforcing spiral of hypoperfusion, ischemia, inflammation, and worsening pump failure."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Hemodynamic definition", "def": "Persistent hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg for >=30 min, or vasopressors/inotropes required to maintain SBP >=90) with a cardiac index typically <2.2 L/min/m2 and a pulmonary capillary wedge pressure >15 mmHg, accompanied by signs of hypoperfusion (cool extremities, oliguria, altered mentation, lactate >2 mmol/L)."}, {"term": "Hypoperfusion without hypotension", "def": "Shock can exist with a preserved blood pressure ('normotensive cardiogenic shock') when intense vasoconstriction maintains MAP at the expense of tissue flow. Lactate and end-organ signs, not the cuff, make this diagnosis."}, {"term": "The shock spiral", "def": "Low output causes coronary and systemic hypoperfusion, which worsens ischemia and contractility, further lowering output. Systemic inflammation adds inappropriate vasodilation and capillary leak, so late shock acquires a distributive component that confounds the classic cold picture."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The SHOCK trial registry taught that a subset of cardiogenic shock patients paradoxically have a low systemic vascular resistance from a SIRS-like inflammatory response with elevated nitric oxide. This is why some late-shock patients look vasodilated and why norepinephrine, a vasoconstrictor with modest inotropy, is often the right first agent rather than a pure inotrope.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "At the myocyte level, ischemic and failing myocardium shows depleted high-energy phosphates, calcium mishandling, and beta-1 receptor downregulation. This underlies two practical truths: catecholamine inotropes become progressively less effective and more arrhythmogenic as shock deepens, and every inotrope buys contractility by raising myocardial oxygen demand, which in an ischemic substrate can extend infarction. Support that unloads the ventricle mechanically, rather than flogging it pharmacologically, is the conceptual appeal of mechanical circulatory support."}]}, {"id": "etiologies", "title": "Etiologies: Not Just Myocardial Infarction", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Acute myocardial infarction accounts for the majority of cardiogenic shock, most often from left ventricular pump failure, but the non-ischemic and mechanical causes are the ones that punish anchoring. A structured differential prevents missing a surgically or mechanically reversible lesion."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "caption": "Major etiologic categories of cardiogenic shock", "head": ["Category", "Representative causes", "Clinical tip"], "rows": [["AMI pump failure", "Large anterior STEMI, extensive ischemia, prior infarct with new insult", "Most common; extent of jeopardized myocardium drives risk"], ["Mechanical complications of MI", "Acute severe MR (papillary muscle rupture), ventricular septal rupture, free-wall rupture", "New murmur plus shock days 3-7 post-MI; needs urgent echo and surgery"], ["Acute decompensated chronic HF", "End-stage HFrEF, HFpEF crisis", "Progressive, often warm-and-wet; advanced-HF/durable-device pathway"], ["Right ventricular failure", "RV infarction, massive/submassive PE, pulmonary hypertension crisis", "Clear lungs plus elevated JVP plus hypotension; preload and RV afterload dependent"], ["Valvular / mechanical", "Acute AR (dissection, endocarditis), acute MR, prosthetic valve thrombosis, critical AS", "Echo is diagnostic; many are surgical emergencies"], ["Myopericardial", "Fulminant myocarditis, stress (Takotsubo) cardiomyopathy, peripartum cardiomyopathy", "Often reversible; bridge to recovery philosophy"], ["Arrhythmic / other", "Incessant VT/VF, complete heart block, tamponade, drug toxicity (beta-blocker/CCB overdose)", "Treat the rhythm or the tamponade first; shock resolves with the cause"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "A new holosystolic murmur with an oxygen step-up from RA to RV (VSD) or with a hyperdynamic small LV and torrential regurgitant jet (papillary muscle rupture) in a patient decompensating 3 to 7 days after MI is a mechanical complication until proven otherwise. These require urgent surgical or transcatheter intervention and temporary MCS as a bridge; inotropes alone will not save them.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the deadly mechanical MI complications: the three R's, <strong>Rupture (free wall), Rupture (septum, i.e. VSD), Regurgitation (papillary muscle)</strong>. All present with abrupt hemodynamic collapse and a new murmur (except free-wall rupture, which presents with tamponade and PEA).", "depth": 1}]}, {"id": "scai-staging", "title": "SCAI SHOCK Staging: The Common Language", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The 2019 SCAI SHOCK classification, updated in 2022, replaced vague labels like 'pre-shock' with a five-stage scheme that maps onto rising mortality and standardizes communication among cardiology, critical care, and surgery. It is the single most useful framework for describing where a patient is and where they are heading."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "caption": "The five SCAI SHOCK stages", "entries": [{"term": "A - At risk", "def": "No current signs or symptoms of shock but at risk (e.g., large acute MI, decompensating HF). Normal lactate, warm and well perfused."}, {"term": "B - Beginning (pre-shock)", "def": "Clinical evidence of relative hypotension or tachycardia without hypoperfusion. Lactate normal; mild volume overload possible. This is the window to intervene."}, {"term": "C - Classic", "def": "Hypoperfusion requiring intervention (inotrope, vasopressor, or mechanical support) beyond volume. Cold, clammy, oliguric; lactate usually >=2. The prototypical shock patient."}, {"term": "D - Deteriorating", "def": "Failing to respond to initial interventions; requires escalation (adding drugs or devices). The trajectory is worsening despite therapy."}, {"term": "E - Extremis", "def": "Circulatory collapse, often with refractory cardiac arrest, ongoing CPR or ECMO, profound acidosis and rising lactate. Near-terminal without immediate rescue."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "SCAI stage with representative bedside, biochemical, and hemodynamic markers", "head": ["Stage", "Physical exam", "Biochemistry", "Hemodynamics", "Approx. in-hospital mortality"], "rows": [["A At risk", "Warm, well perfused, normal JVP", "Normal lactate, normal renal function", "Normal BP and CI", "Low single digits"], ["B Beginning", "Elevated JVP, tachycardia, warm extremities", "Normal lactate, minimal renal change", "SBP <90 or MAP <60 or >30 mmHg drop", "Roughly 7-10%"], ["C Classic", "Cool, clammy, mottled, volume overload, altered mentation", "Lactate >=2, creatinine rising, BNP up", "CI <2.2, PCWP >15, needs pressors/inotropes", "Roughly 20-30%"], ["D Deteriorating", "Worsening perfusion despite therapy", "Lactate rising or not clearing", "Requires added drug or device", "Roughly 40%"], ["E Extremis", "Near-pulseless, mottled, obtunded", "Lactate often >8-10, severe acidosis (pH <7.2)", "Refractory collapse, CPR/ECMO", "Roughly 60% or higher"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Two modifiers refine the stage. A cardiac-arrest modifier (the letter <strong>A</strong> appended, e.g. 'C-A') denotes cardiac arrest, which independently worsens prognosis at every stage. The 2022 update also formalized a three-axis assessment (physical exam, biomarkers, hemodynamics) and a 'risk gradient' within stages, recognizing that a stage C patient on rising lactate is closer to D than one whose lactate is clearing. Stage is dynamic; restage frequently.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the SCAI ladder: <strong>A-B-C-D-E = At risk, Beginning, Classic, Deteriorating, Extremis</strong>. Reinforce it as 'the sicker the letter, the worse the lactate.' Lactate and its clearance are the through-line that connect the stages.", "depth": 1}]}, {"id": "clinical-presentation", "title": "Clinical Presentation and Phenotyping", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Bedside phenotyping answers two questions before any number returns: which ventricle is failing, and is the patient wet or dry, warm or cold. These determine whether you give volume, unload, vasoconstrict, or inodilate."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Forward (low-output) signs", "def": "Cool and mottled extremities, narrow pulse pressure, delayed capillary refill, oliguria, altered mentation, rising lactate. These reflect inadequate cardiac output."}, {"term": "Backward (congestive) signs", "def": "Elevated JVP, pulmonary rales and hypoxemia (left-sided), hepatic congestion and peripheral edema (right-sided). These reflect elevated filling pressures."}, {"term": "The Stevenson 2x2", "def": "Warm/cold (perfusion) crossed with dry/wet (congestion). Cold-and-wet is the classic dangerous cardiogenic-shock quadrant; cold-and-dry suggests hypovolemia or end-stage low-output; warm-and-wet is decompensated congestion."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the Stevenson quadrants: <strong>warm/cold, dry/wet</strong>. 'Cold and wet' is the shock patient you fear; 'warm and dry' is the goal of resuscitation. Move patients toward the warm-and-dry quadrant.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Isolated right ventricular shock (RV infarction or acute PE) looks different and is a classic trap: clear lung fields, elevated JVP, and hypotension. These patients are <strong>preload dependent</strong> and can be worsened by aggressive nitrates, diuresis, or excessive PEEP. Give judicious volume, support the RV, and reduce RV afterload; do not reflexively diurese a hypotensive patient with clear lungs.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "diagnostic-approach", "title": "Diagnostic Approach and Invasive Hemodynamics", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The initial workup is fast and parallel: ECG for STEMI or arrhythmia, bedside echo to identify the failing ventricle and mechanical lesions, lactate and end-organ labs to grade severity, and early consideration of a pulmonary artery catheter to phenotype and follow the response. The ESCAPE trial cooled enthusiasm for routine PACs in general decompensated HF, but contemporary shock registries suggest complete invasive hemodynamic profiling is associated with better outcomes in cardiogenic shock specifically."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Key hemodynamic parameters and their shock thresholds", "head": ["Parameter", "Formula / source", "Normal", "Shock threshold", "Meaning"], "rows": [["Cardiac index", "CO / BSA", "2.5-4.0 L/min/m2", "<2.2 (or <1.8 without support)", "Low-output state"], ["PCWP", "PA catheter wedge", "6-12 mmHg", ">15-18", "LV congestion / preload"], ["Cardiac power output (CPO)", "MAP x CO / 451", "~1.0 W", "<0.6 W", "Strongest hemodynamic mortality predictor (SHOCK)"], ["PAPi", "(PASP - PADP) / RAP", "context dependent", "<1.0 (acute RVMI); <1.85 (post-LVAD)", "Low value predicts RV failure"], ["RA pressure", "PA catheter", "2-6 mmHg", "Elevated; RA/PCWP >0.8 suggests RV predominance", "RV involvement"], ["SvO2 / ScvO2", "Mixed venous sat", "65-75%", "<60%", "Global oxygen supply-demand deficit"], ["Systemic vascular resistance", "80 x (MAP-RAP)/CO", "800-1200 dyn.s/cm5", "High (cold) or low (vasodilated/mixed)", "Distinguishes vasoconstricted vs SIRS phenotype"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>Cardiac power output</strong> is the number to internalize. In the SHOCK trial hemodynamic analysis, CPO was the single strongest independent predictor of in-hospital mortality. A CPO below ~0.6 W identifies a ventricle that cannot generate enough flow-pressure product to sustain perfusion and is a concrete trigger to consider mechanical support rather than escalating catecholamines.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>PAPi</strong> = (PA systolic - PA diastolic) / RA pressure. A low PAPi means the RV cannot generate pulsatile pressure against its afterload while the RA pressure is high, i.e., a failing RV. Thresholds around <0.9-1.0 flag acute RV infarction shock and around <1.85 predict RV failure after LVAD. When you are deciding whether an LV device alone will suffice or whether the RV will collapse and demand biventricular support, PAPi is the number.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "To recognize RV-strain and infarction patterns (right precordial ST elevation on right-sided leads V3R-V4R in RV infarction, and the S1Q3T3 pattern of acute right-heart strain) that accompany cardiogenic shock, review annotated 12-lead examples.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library"}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "For the imaging correlates of shock etiologies (pulmonary edema, RV dilation and septal bowing in acute PE, ventricular septal rupture, pericardial effusion with tamponade physiology), review the cross-sectional and echo teaching cases.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia"}]}, {"id": "initial-stabilization", "title": "Initial Stabilization and the Shock Team", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The first hour is about restoring a perfusing pressure, reversing the precipitant, and deciding the trajectory. In AMI shock, emergent revascularization of the culprit lesion is the single intervention with the strongest mortality evidence, established by the SHOCK trial."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["Initial approach to suspected cardiogenic shock"], "items": ["Confirm the diagnosis and phenotype: ECG, bedside echo (which ventricle, effusion, mechanical lesion), lactate, and end-organ labs.", "Secure airway and oxygenation; use non-invasive ventilation judiciously, recognizing that intubation and positive pressure reduce preload and can precipitate collapse in a marginal RV.", "Establish arterial line and central access; start norepinephrine as first-line vasopressor to restore MAP >=65 mmHg.", "Assess volume carefully: cautious fluid challenge only if under-filled (dry RV physiology); most classic LV shock is already congested and needs unloading, not volume.", "Reverse the precipitant: emergent PCI of the culprit vessel in AMI shock (culprit-lesion-only per CULPRIT-SHOCK), treat arrhythmia, drain tamponade, thrombolyse or perform thrombectomy for massive PE.", "Grade with SCAI stage, measure CPO and lactate, and activate the shock team early to plan escalation before deterioration."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The <strong>CULPRIT-SHOCK</strong> trial showed that in multivessel disease with AMI shock, culprit-lesion-only PCI improved 30-day death or renal-replacement outcomes compared with immediate complete multivessel revascularization. Fix the culprit, stabilize, and stage non-culprit lesions later rather than doing everything at once in an unstable patient.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The rise of the multidisciplinary <strong>shock team</strong> (interventional cardiology, heart failure/MCS, cardiac surgery, critical care) is associated in registries with better survival, largely by standardizing early phenotyping, appropriate device selection, and avoiding both under- and over-escalation. Activate it early, in stage B-C, not at stage E.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "vasopressors-inotropes", "title": "DEEP DIVE: Vasopressors and Inotropes", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Pharmacologic support in cardiogenic shock is a mechanistic exercise in balancing three variables: contractility, systemic vascular tone, and myocardial oxygen demand. Every catecholamine raises oxygen demand and is proarrhythmic, and none has been shown to improve survival, so the goal is the lowest effective support to bridge to reversal or to a device."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "caption": "Vasopressors and inotropes in cardiogenic shock: receptor, dose, indication, and key adverse effect", "head": ["Agent", "Receptor / mechanism", "Dose range", "Primary indication", "Key adverse effect"], "rows": [["Norepinephrine", "Alpha-1 >> beta-1 (vasoconstrictor with modest inotropy)", "0.05-0.5 mcg/kg/min (occasionally higher)", "First-line vasopressor in cardiogenic shock (fewer arrhythmias than dopamine)", "Peripheral/organ ischemia, reflex bradycardia, increased LV afterload"], ["Epinephrine", "Beta-1 and beta-2 (lower dose), alpha-1 (higher dose)", "0.01-0.5 mcg/kg/min", "Refractory shock, peri-arrest, post-cardiotomy; potent inopressor", "Marked tachyarrhythmia, lactic acidosis (beta-2 driven), increased myocardial O2 demand"], ["Dopamine", "Dose-dependent: dopaminergic (low), beta-1 (mid), alpha-1 (high)", "2-20 mcg/kg/min", "Shock with relative bradycardia (rarely first-line now)", "More arrhythmias and higher mortality vs norepinephrine in the cardiogenic-shock subgroup (SOAP II)"], ["Dobutamine", "Beta-1 >> beta-2 agonist (inodilator)", "2-20 mcg/kg/min", "Low-output state with adequate BP; augment CO", "Tachycardia/arrhythmia, hypotension (beta-2 vasodilation), blunted by beta-blockade"], ["Milrinone", "PDE3 inhibitor, raises cAMP downstream of the beta receptor (inodilator)", "0.125-0.75 mcg/kg/min (loading dose usually omitted in shock)", "Beta-blocked patients, RV failure / pulmonary hypertension, preserved BP", "Hypotension, ventricular arrhythmia, accumulation in renal impairment (renally cleared)"], ["Vasopressin", "V1 receptor (non-adrenergic vasoconstriction)", "0.01-0.04 units/min (fixed dose, not weight-titrated)", "Adjunct to norepinephrine; vasodilatory/SIRS phenotype; raises SVR without added chronotropy", "Splanchnic/digital/coronary ischemia, hyponatremia; relatively spares the pulmonary circulation (advantage in RV failure)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>DOREMI</strong> (2021) randomized cardiogenic shock patients to milrinone versus dobutamine and found no significant difference in the primary composite of in-hospital death, resuscitated cardiac arrest, MCS, MI, stroke, or renal replacement. The practical message: there is no evidence-mandated winner, so choose mechanistically. Favor milrinone for the beta-blocked patient with RV/pulmonary-hypertension physiology and preserved pressure and renal function; favor dobutamine when the pressure is marginal or renal clearance is poor.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "<strong>SOAP II</strong> compared dopamine with norepinephrine across all-cause shock. Overall 28-day mortality was similar, but dopamine caused significantly more arrhythmias, and in the pre-specified cardiogenic-shock subgroup it was associated with higher mortality. This is the trial behind the modern default of <strong>norepinephrine first</strong> in cardiogenic shock. A small trial of epinephrine versus norepinephrine in AMI shock (OptimaCC) was stopped early for more refractory shock and lactic acidosis with epinephrine.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for choosing the vasoactive: <strong>'Pressure or pump?'</strong> If the problem is inadequate blood pressure (low SVR / vasoplegia), reach for a vaso<strong>pressor</strong> (norepinephrine, add vasopressin). If the problem is inadequate flow with acceptable pressure, reach for an ino<strong>trope</strong> (dobutamine or milrinone, the 'inodilators'). Most real shock needs both, which is why norepinephrine plus dobutamine is a common starting pair.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "caption": "Inodilator contrasts worth memorizing", "entries": [{"term": "Dobutamine", "def": "Beta-1 agonist; onset in minutes, hepatically cleared, short half-life (~2 min). Efficacy blunted by chronic beta-blockade. Can drop SVR via beta-2. Best when perfusion pressure is marginal and renal function poor."}, {"term": "Milrinone", "def": "PDE3 inhibitor acting downstream of the beta receptor, so it works despite beta-blockade. Lowers PVR and SVR (helpful in RV failure and pulmonary hypertension), but is renally cleared (accumulates in AKI) and more hypotensive. Best with preserved BP and renal function."}, {"term": "Vasopressin as an RV-sparing pressor", "def": "Because vasopressin raises systemic vascular resistance with relatively little effect on the pulmonary circulation, it is a favored adjunct pressor in right ventricular shock, where you want to defend systemic MAP (and thus RV coronary perfusion) without raising RV afterload."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Do not chase a target blood pressure by stacking escalating catecholamines in a patient whose CPO stays below ~0.6 W and whose lactate keeps rising. Escalating inotropes in an ischemic ventricle increases oxygen demand and arrhythmia and can extend infarction. Persistent low CPO despite two vasoactives is a signal to escalate to mechanical support, not to add a third drug.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "escalation-mcs", "title": "DEEP DIVE: When and How to Escalate to Mechanical Support", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Temporary mechanical circulatory support exists to restore perfusion and unload the failing ventricle when drugs are insufficient, buying time for recovery, for a durable decision, or for transplant. The decision to escalate is driven by trajectory: rising lactate, falling CPO, worsening SCAI stage, and end-organ injury despite adequate pharmacologic support."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "caption": "Temporary mechanical circulatory support options", "head": ["Device", "Mechanism / support", "Flow", "Notable feature", "Key limitation"], "rows": [["IABP", "Counterpulsation: diastolic augmentation, systolic afterload reduction", "~0.5-1 L/min effective", "Easy, familiar, modest coronary perfusion boost", "No mortality benefit in AMI shock (IABP-SHOCK II)"], ["Microaxial flow pump (Impella)", "Trans-valvular axial pump, LV to aorta; directly unloads LV", "2.5-6.0 L/min by model", "Active LV unloading, reduces wall stress and O2 demand", "Limb/vascular injury, hemolysis, bleeding; needs adequate RV and no severe AI/LV thrombus"], ["TandemHeart", "Trans-septal LA-to-femoral-artery bypass", "up to ~4 L/min", "Bypasses the LV directly", "Trans-septal puncture, complex, LA cannula risks"], ["VA-ECMO", "Venoarterial extracorporeal support: full cardiopulmonary support", "4-6+ L/min", "Supports oxygenation and both ventricles; use in arrest/biventricular failure", "Raises LV afterload (may need venting/'ECpella'), limb ischemia, bleeding, no routine survival benefit (ECLS-SHOCK)"], ["RV support (Impella RP / ProtekDuo)", "Dedicated RV bypass, RA/IVC to PA", "up to ~4 L/min", "For isolated or LVAD-associated RV failure", "Adds complexity; requires recognition of the RV as the failing chamber"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Landmark device evidence, held together: <strong>IABP-SHOCK II</strong> (2012) showed no 30-day or long-term mortality benefit of routine IABP in AMI cardiogenic shock, demoting it from reflex first choice. <strong>ECLS-SHOCK</strong> (2023) showed that routine early VA-ECMO in AMI shock did not reduce 30-day mortality and increased bleeding and vascular complications. <strong>DanGer Shock</strong> (2024) was the first RCT to show a mortality reduction with a microaxial flow pump (Impella CP) in selected STEMI-related shock, though at the cost of more renal-replacement therapy, bleeding, and limb complications.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The DanGer Shock population is the fine print. Benefit was shown in <strong>STEMI-related shock, excluding patients with out-of-hospital cardiac arrest who remained comatose</strong>, that is, patients with a salvageable brain and a recoverable LV. It is not evidence to place an Impella in every shock patient, and the complication burden is real. Selection is everything: a good candidate is an isolated LV-failure shock with adequate RV function and no prohibitive vascular disease.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "head": ["A pragmatic escalation ladder"], "items": ["Optimize the reversible cause first (revascularize, fix the mechanical lesion, treat the rhythm or tamponade).", "Restore MAP with norepinephrine; add an inotrope (dobutamine or milrinone) for low output with an acceptable pressure.", "Reassess in a tight loop: lactate clearance, CPO, urine output, mentation, and SCAI stage every few hours.", "If CPO stays <0.6 W, lactate fails to clear, or the SCAI stage deteriorates on two vasoactives, escalate to temporary MCS rather than adding a third drug.", "Match the device to the failing ventricle: LV support (Impella) for isolated LV shock, dedicated RV support or VA-ECMO for RV or biventricular failure, and consider LV venting when VA-ECMO raises LV afterload.", "Define the exit strategy at the moment of escalation: bridge to recovery, bridge to durable device, bridge to transplant, or bridge to decision. A device without an exit plan is a trap."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "VA-ECMO restores systemic flow but retrogradely raises LV afterload, which can distend a stunned LV, worsen pulmonary edema, and prevent recovery. Watch for a non-opening aortic valve, rising PA/wedge pressures, and worsening pulmonary edema, and be ready to <strong>vent the LV</strong> (with an IABP, an Impella in the 'ECpella' configuration, or atrial septostomy). Failing to recognize LV distension on ECMO is a classic and lethal oversight.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "rv-shock", "title": "DEEP DIVE: Right Ventricular Cardiogenic Shock", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Right ventricular shock deserves its own model because its management inverts several LV-shock instincts. The RV is a thin-walled, preload-dependent, afterload-intolerant pump; when it fails, systemic hypotension arises from inadequate LV filling, not from LV contractile failure."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Causes: RV infarction (usually inferior MI with proximal RCA occlusion), acute massive/submassive PE, pulmonary hypertension crisis, and RV failure after LVAD.", "Presentation: hypotension with elevated JVP and clear lungs; Kussmaul sign; hypotension after nitrates. On the PA catheter, high RA pressure, low PAPi, and a high RA/PCWP ratio.", "Preload: maintain it. Cautious volume if under-filled, but avoid over-distension, which bows the septum leftward and impairs LV filling.", "Afterload: reduce RV afterload with oxygen, avoidance of hypercarbia and acidosis, and selective pulmonary vasodilators (inhaled nitric oxide or inhaled prostacyclin) when pulmonary hypertension drives failure.", "Perfusion: defend systemic MAP to preserve RV coronary perfusion. Norepinephrine and vasopressin are preferred; vasopressin relatively spares the pulmonary circulation.", "Contractility and rhythm: dobutamine or milrinone for RV inotropy; restore AV synchrony, since the failing RV depends heavily on atrial kick, and rate-control tachyarrhythmia."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for RV failure management, the <strong>'optimize preload, reduce afterload, support contractility, maintain perfusion and rhythm'</strong> sequence. A compact version: <strong>P-A-C-E</strong> = Preload (optimize, don't overfill), Afterload (reduce: O2, avoid acidosis, pulmonary vasodilators), Contractility (inotrope), and Electrical/perfusion (AV synchrony plus systemic MAP for RV coronary flow).", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Intubation and positive-pressure ventilation are perilous in RV shock: sedation drops sympathetic tone and preload, and positive intrathoracic pressure raises RV afterload and reduces venous return, which can precipitate arrest. If intubation is unavoidable, optimize the RV first, use a hemodynamically stable induction, and keep tidal volumes and PEEP modest.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "pitfalls-adjuncts", "title": "Adjuncts, Monitoring, and Trajectory", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Beyond drugs and devices, outcomes turn on disciplined monitoring and on treating the whole shock physiology, including the systemic and metabolic consequences."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Lactate clearance is the most useful single trajectory marker; a lactate that halves over 6-12 hours signals response, while a rising lactate on adequate support demands escalation.", "Serial CPO and PAPi (if a PA catheter is in place) quantify LV and RV recovery and guide weaning.", "Maintain MAP >=65 mmHg, but individualize; the RV coronary and the injured brain may need higher targets.", "Correct the metabolic milieu: acidosis blunts catecholamine responsiveness and worsens pulmonary vascular tone; treat the cause rather than reflexively bicarbonating.", "Renal replacement for refractory volume overload and metabolic derangement; cardiorenal syndrome is common and worsens prognosis.", "Anticipate and prevent device complications: hemolysis and limb ischemia with Impella and ECMO, bleeding from anticoagulation, and infection."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Weaning is as deliberate as escalation. Wean the vasoactive or device only when lactate has cleared, CPO has recovered (trending toward or above ~0.6-0.8 W), filling pressures have normalized, and the underlying insult is treated. Premature weaning that drops CPO back below threshold restarts the shock spiral and worsens cumulative organ injury.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "advanced-fellow-concepts", "title": "Advanced Fellow Concepts", "body": [{"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Cardiac power output (CPO)", "def": "MAP x cardiac output / 451, in watts. Below ~0.6 W it is the strongest hemodynamic predictor of in-hospital mortality in cardiogenic shock (SHOCK trial analysis) and a concrete escalation trigger."}, {"term": "Aortic pulsatility and native ejection on MCS", "def": "On VA-ECMO or Impella, whether the aortic valve opens each beat reflects the balance of native LV ejection against device afterload. A persistently closed valve on ECMO signals LV distension and the need for venting."}, {"term": "Normotensive cardiogenic shock", "def": "Hypoperfusion (lactate, cold, oliguria) despite a preserved cuff pressure, sustained by intense vasoconstriction. Carries substantial mortality and is easily missed if you anchor on blood pressure alone."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The intellectual center of shock decision-making is asking, for every patient, <strong>'which chamber, how much reserve, and what is the exit?'</strong> Identifying the failing ventricle (CPO for the LV, PAPi and RA/PCWP for the RV) determines the device; estimating recoverability (myocarditis and Takotsubo often recover, extensive infarction may not) determines whether you are bridging to recovery, to a durable device, or to transplant.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Fulminant myocarditis and Takotsubo (stress) cardiomyopathy are the great arguments for aggressive temporary support: both can present in extremis yet frequently recover fully within days to weeks if the patient is carried through the nadir. This 'bridge to recovery' philosophy justifies escalating to VA-ECMO or microaxial support in a young patient in refractory shock from a potentially reversible myopathy, where a durable decision can await recovery."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Prognostic scores formalize the gestalt: the IABP-SHOCK II score (age, prior stroke, admission glucose, creatinine, arterial lactate, and TIMI flow after PCI) risk-stratifies AMI shock, and the SCAI stage with the cardiac-arrest modifier stratifies mixed shock. They are decision aids that sharpen, but never replace, the bedside trajectory of lactate, CPO, and end-organ function."}]}, {"id": "bedside-pearls", "title": "Bedside Pearls", "body": [{"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Escalate on the slope, not the snapshot. A single blood pressure lies; a rising lactate and a falling CPO on adequate support tell the truth about where the patient is heading.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Hypotension with clear lungs and a big JVP is RV shock until proven otherwise. Give volume cautiously, protect the pressure with norepinephrine or vasopressin, and do not diurese reflexively.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Norepinephrine is the default first vasoactive in cardiogenic shock; dopamine buys you arrhythmias and, in the cardiogenic subgroup of SOAP II, worse survival.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "When milrinone seems to be failing in a hypotensive patient, remember it is a renally-cleared vasodilator: accumulation and hypotension may be the problem. Reassess renal function, add a pressor to defend MAP, or switch to dobutamine.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "On VA-ECMO, if the aortic valve stops opening and pulmonary edema worsens, the LV is distending. Vent it early; a distended, non-ejecting LV will not recover.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "common-mistakes", "title": "Common Mistakes", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Anchoring on blood pressure and missing normotensive cardiogenic shock, where lactate and cold extremities are the only clues.", "Reflexively diuresing a hypotensive patient with clear lungs and elevated JVP, worsening a preload-dependent RV.", "Reaching for dopamine as a first-line agent, incurring arrhythmia and, in cardiogenic shock, worse outcomes than norepinephrine.", "Stacking escalating catecholamines in a patient with persistently low CPO and rising lactate instead of escalating to mechanical support.", "Placing an IABP reflexively in AMI shock as if it changed mortality (IABP-SHOCK II showed it does not) or placing routine early VA-ECMO expecting a survival benefit (ECLS-SHOCK showed none).", "Extrapolating DanGer Shock to every patient rather than the selected STEMI, isolated-LV-failure population it studied, and ignoring the real complication burden.", "Failing to recognize and vent LV distension on VA-ECMO, preventing recovery and worsening pulmonary edema.", "Escalating to a device without defining the exit strategy (recovery, durable device, transplant, or decision) at the outset."]}]}, {"id": "references", "title": "References", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["SCAI Clinical Expert Consensus on the Classification of Cardiogenic Shock (2019) and 2022 Update.", "2021 ESC and 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Heart Failure Guidelines; 2023 ESC ACS guideline statements on cardiogenic shock management.", "DOREMI Trial (milrinone vs dobutamine in cardiogenic shock).", "IABP-SHOCK II, DanGer Shock, and ECLS-SHOCK trials of mechanical circulatory support.", "SHOCK Trial and Registry (early revascularization; cardiac power output as mortality predictor).", "SOAP II Trial (dopamine vs norepinephrine) and CULPRIT-SHOCK Trial (culprit-only PCI)."]}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 61-year-old man is admitted with a large anterior STEMI. After primary PCI he is cool and mottled with SBP 82 mmHg, lactate 4.2 mmol/L, and urine output 10 mL/hr. A PA catheter shows cardiac index 1.7 L/min/m2, PCWP 24 mmHg, and MAP 62 mmHg with a calculated cardiac power output of 0.48 W. He is already on norepinephrine and dobutamine at moderate doses, and the lactate has risen from 3.1 over the last four hours. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Add a third vasoactive agent (epinephrine) and continue medical therapy"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Escalate to temporary mechanical circulatory support with LV unloading"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Aggressively diurese to lower the wedge pressure"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Place an intra-aortic balloon pump for definitive mortality benefit"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Reduce norepinephrine to lower afterload"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is isolated LV-failure cardiogenic shock that is deteriorating (SCAI stage D) despite two vasoactives, with a cardiac power output below the ~0.6 W threshold and a rising lactate. The correct move is to escalate to mechanical support that unloads the LV (a microaxial flow pump), consistent with the DanGer Shock population. Stacking a third catecholamine raises myocardial oxygen demand and arrhythmia without addressing inadequate flow. IABP does not confer a mortality benefit in AMI shock (IABP-SHOCK II). Diuresis in a hypotensive low-output patient risks further compromising output, and lowering norepinephrine would worsen perfusion pressure."}, {"stem": "A 48-year-old woman with an inferior STEMI becomes hypotensive (SBP 84 mmHg). Her lungs are clear, JVP is markedly elevated, and she becomes more hypotensive after a dose of sublingual nitroglycerin. PA catheter shows RA pressure 18 mmHg, PA 30/16, PCWP 12, and a low PAPi. Which management approach is most appropriate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Aggressive IV furosemide to reduce the elevated JVP"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Cautious volume, norepinephrine or vasopressin to maintain MAP, and avoidance of preload reduction"}, {"key": "C", "text": "High-dose nitroglycerin infusion to unload the ventricle"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Immediate durable LVAD implantation"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Start high-dose milrinone as the sole agent"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The clear lungs, elevated JVP, low PAPi, high RA pressure, and hypotension after nitrates are classic for right ventricular infarction shock. The RV is preload dependent and afterload intolerant, so management is to optimize (not deplete) preload, defend systemic MAP to preserve RV coronary perfusion (norepinephrine, or vasopressin, which relatively spares the pulmonary circulation), and avoid preload-reducing agents. Diuresis and nitrates worsen a preload-dependent RV. Milrinone alone is inappropriate because its vasodilation would drop the systemic pressure the failing RV needs. A durable LVAD is not an emergency step here."}, {"stem": "A patient in cardiogenic shock on chronic carvedilol has a cardiac index of 1.9 L/min/m2, PCWP 22 mmHg, elevated pulmonary vascular resistance, an adequate MAP of 72 mmHg on low-dose norepinephrine, and normal renal function. You wish to add an inotrope to augment output. Which agent best fits the physiology, and what does the evidence say about the choice?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Dobutamine, because DOREMI proved it superior to milrinone"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Milrinone, because it works despite beta-blockade and lowers pulmonary vascular resistance, though DOREMI showed the two inotropes are clinically equivalent"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Dopamine, because it is the guideline-preferred inotrope in shock"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Epinephrine, because it has the best mortality data in cardiogenic shock"}, {"key": "E", "text": "No inotrope; increase the beta-blocker dose"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Milrinone is a PDE3 inhibitor acting downstream of the beta receptor, so its inotropy is preserved despite chronic beta-blockade, and its pulmonary vasodilation is advantageous with elevated PVR. The preserved MAP and normal renal function make its hypotension and renal accumulation manageable. DOREMI found no significant difference between milrinone and dobutamine, so neither is proven superior; the choice is mechanistic. Dopamine is associated with more arrhythmia and worse outcomes in cardiogenic shock (SOAP II), epinephrine has no mortality advantage and causes more lactic acidosis, and up-titrating the beta-blocker in shock is dangerous."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old man with AMI cardiogenic shock is placed on peripheral VA-ECMO for refractory hypotension. Over the next several hours his oxygenation worsens with new diffuse pulmonary edema, and bedside echo shows a dilated left ventricle with an aortic valve that no longer opens. What is the most appropriate intervention?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Increase ECMO flow to improve systemic perfusion"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Add an LV venting strategy (e.g., IABP or Impella) to decompress the distended left ventricle"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Discontinue anticoagulation to reduce bleeding"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Start aggressive diuresis alone and continue current support"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Transition immediately to comfort care"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "VA-ECMO provides retrograde aortic flow that raises LV afterload; a stunned LV can distend, the aortic valve stops opening, and pulmonary edema worsens, all of which impair recovery. The correct response is to unload or vent the LV, commonly by adding an IABP or an Impella (the 'ECpella' configuration) or, less commonly, atrial septostomy. Increasing ECMO flow worsens LV afterload. Stopping anticoagulation risks circuit thrombosis and does not address distension, and diuresis alone will not relieve the mechanical afterload problem."}, {"stem": "Which statement about the trial evidence for mechanical circulatory support in cardiogenic shock is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "IABP-SHOCK II showed that routine IABP reduces 30-day mortality in AMI shock"}, {"key": "B", "text": "ECLS-SHOCK showed that routine early VA-ECMO reduced mortality in AMI shock"}, {"key": "C", "text": "DanGer Shock showed a mortality reduction with a microaxial flow pump in selected STEMI-related shock, with more bleeding, renal-replacement, and limb complications"}, {"key": "D", "text": "DOREMI demonstrated that milrinone is markedly superior to dobutamine for survival"}, {"key": "E", "text": "All three device trials showed a consistent mortality benefit for early routine device placement"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "DanGer Shock (2024) was the first RCT to show a mortality reduction with a microaxial flow pump (Impella CP) in a selected STEMI shock population, at the cost of more complications. IABP-SHOCK II showed no mortality benefit of routine IABP in AMI shock. ECLS-SHOCK showed routine early VA-ECMO did not reduce 30-day mortality and increased bleeding and vascular complications. DOREMI found no significant difference between milrinone and dobutamine. Device benefit is therefore patient-specific, not a blanket endorsement of early routine support."}, {"stem": "A patient with a large MI has SBP 88 mmHg and tachycardia but is warm with normal lactate, normal creatinine, and no evidence of hypoperfusion. Using the SCAI SHOCK classification, which stage best describes this patient and what is the principal implication?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Stage A; no intervention or monitoring is warranted"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Stage B (Beginning/pre-shock); this is the window to intervene before hypoperfusion develops"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Stage C (Classic); start inotropes and pressors immediately"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Stage D (Deteriorating); escalate to mechanical support"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Stage E (Extremis); initiate ECMO"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Relative hypotension and tachycardia without hypoperfusion (normal lactate and end-organ function) define SCAI stage B, or 'beginning' shock. Recognizing stage B matters because it is the window to intervene, by treating the precipitant, monitoring closely, and activating the shock team, before the patient progresses to classic hypoperfused shock. Stage A would have no hemodynamic abnormality at all. Stages C through E all require evidence of hypoperfusion or refractory collapse that this patient does not yet have, so drugs, devices, or ECMO would be premature."}], "references": ["SCAI Clinical Expert Consensus Statement on the Classification of Cardiogenic Shock (2019) and 2022 Update", "2021 ESC and 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Heart Failure Guidelines; 2023 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes", "DOREMI Trial: Milrinone versus Dobutamine in Cardiogenic Shock (NEJM 2021)", "IABP-SHOCK II Trial: Intra-Aortic Balloon Pump in Acute Myocardial Infarction Cardiogenic Shock", "DanGer Shock Trial: Microaxial Flow Pump (Impella CP) in STEMI-Related Cardiogenic Shock (NEJM 2024)", "ECLS-SHOCK Trial: Early Venoarterial ECMO in Infarct-Related Cardiogenic Shock", "SHOCK Trial and Registry: Early Revascularization and Cardiac Power Output as a Mortality Predictor", "SOAP II Trial (Dopamine vs Norepinephrine) and CULPRIT-SHOCK Trial (Culprit-Lesion-Only PCI)"], "guidelines": [{"society": "SCAI", "text": "Cardiogenic shock should be classified using the standardized SCAI SHOCK stages (A At risk, B Beginning, C Classic, D Deteriorating, E Extremis), integrating physical exam, biochemical markers, and hemodynamics, with a cardiac-arrest modifier, to stratify risk and guide communication and escalation.", "year": "2022"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "Emergency revascularization of the culprit vessel by PCI or CABG is recommended in patients with cardiogenic shock complicating acute myocardial infarction, irrespective of the time delay from symptom onset.", "cor": "I", "loe": "B-R", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "In patients with cardiogenic shock and multivessel disease, routine immediate revascularization of non-culprit lesions is not recommended during the index primary PCI procedure (a culprit-lesion-only strategy is preferred).", "cor": "III", "loe": "B", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC/HFSA", "text": "Norepinephrine is a reasonable first-line vasopressor to restore perfusion pressure in cardiogenic shock, given the higher rate of arrhythmias and worse outcomes observed with dopamine in the cardiogenic-shock population.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "B-NR", "year": "2022"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC/SCAI", "text": "Routine use of intra-aortic balloon counterpulsation is not recommended for patients with acute myocardial infarction complicated by cardiogenic shock, as it has not been shown to reduce mortality.", "cor": "III", "loe": "B-R", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "Short-term mechanical circulatory support may be considered in selected patients with cardiogenic shock, as a bridge to recovery, to a durable device, or to transplantation, with device choice individualized to the failing ventricle and the clinical trajectory.", "cor": "IIb", "loe": "C", "year": "2021"}]};
